The Economy of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly a topic in the news, and therefore many would probably say war.
However, this turns out to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-efficient solutions for this and other global problems.
It is obvious that everyone would like to end war and violence, just like we would like to end poverty, hunger, and climate change, and provide access to education for all people.
However, given limited resources, there are boundaries to what the international community can do.
We have to set priorities, and one can use an economic cost-benefit analysis for that.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals they consider to be the most sensible from their point of view.
Is it worth the investment to reduce violence, considering that the resources that would be used for this could otherwise be used, for example, to combat hunger?
And, if yes, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon of Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies of Oxford University, violence in society – murders, and especially violence against women and children – is a much greater problem than civil wars.
For every casualty on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries record murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization describes as an epidemic.
A single murder in America costs a human life and society $9.1 million in US dollars.
Measured against global national income, this form of violent crime costs the world 1.7% of its gross domestic product (GDP).
Of course, this is not a direct financial loss for the world economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies around the world would be in a better state, which can be quantified at 1.7% of GDP.
Let's compare this to the noticeably lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to around 0.2% of global GDP.
However, this is still much less than the largest source of violence of all: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in Africa south of the Sahara experienced violence by their partners or family members last year.
This includes women who were beaten, forcibly married at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and victims of genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the follow-up costs for society alone by violence from partners amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is committed by parents 80% of the time.
The definition of what constitutes child abuse varies from culture to culture, but around 15% of children experience every month what the UN describes as severe physical corporal punishment.
Among these are blows to the face, head, or ears, and a quarter of these children are repeatedly and as harshly as possible struck with an object.
This suffering is inflicted on around 290 million children every month.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of the global GDP.
Only a tiny fraction of international aid currently flows into reducing violence in society and improving the criminal justice system.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals are practically screaming for something to be done.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any secure findings on where the limited funds should be used best.
All that can be said is that the money spent to reduce violence could be used more targetingly.
Large sums of aid money are destined for "fragile states" to help contribute to ending or preventing civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component of "crime prevention".
Other programs can contribute indirectly, but it is clearly evident that much could be done better.
Some solutions, it is clear, work very well.
More capable social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that home visits by trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life of children, and their physical and mental health, and reduce the costs of care and procedure costs.
A dollar spent on this program generates a benefit worth 14 US dollars: It is therefore an extremely cost-effective measure.
In many cases, social attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda by the name of SASA! is working.
(Kisuaheli for 'Now!' - and that's for spreading the view that violence in a partnership is unacceptable - and that has contributed to halving the number of cases.)
That's a fantastic result - even if there is no analysis of cost efficiency available.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach - a time limit for the sale of alcohol, the recovery of public space, and improvements in the police and justice system - the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
This is still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks, and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations has shown that physical attacks can be reduced in a very cost-efficient manner, with the benefit outweighing the costs in a ratio of 17 to one.
We still do not know enough, but two points are clear: First, domestic violence against women and children costs society $8 billion per year and thus represents a huge – and too little noticed – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can contribute to addressing some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, reducing household violence belongs to the narrower selection of the world's next development goals.
